Maecenas had urged Horace again and again to finish up some col- lection of verses, probably the book oi epodes. Horace answers that he cannot now, sor he is in love, and even Anacreon could not write polished verses when smitten with Bathyllus. The poem closes with the retort: ‘You too are in love, Maecenas, and should understand-3 thank Heaven that your flame is not like mine) The colloquial and familiar tone of the epode should be noticed.
